<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,474,1772,1798]" box="[151,474,1772,1798]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,474,1772,1798]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" reason="1">
<taxonomicName authority="Ashmead, 1904" authorityName="Ashmead." authorityYear="1904" box="[151,474,1772,1798]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,474,1772,1798]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1772,1798]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Aximopsis</emphasis>
Ashmead, 1904
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1436,1842,2011]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<bibRefCitation author="Lotfalizadeh" box="[151,436,1842,1867]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Lotfalizadeh" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="441 - 510" refId="ref49366" refString="Lotfalizadeh, H., Delvare, G. &amp; Rasplus, J. - Y. (2007) Phylogenetic analysis of Eurytominae (Chalcidoidea: Eurytomidae) based on morphological characters. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 151, 441 - 510. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2007.00308. x" type="journal article" year="2007">
Lotfalizadeh 
<emphasis box="[299,355,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">et al.</emphasis>
(2007)
</bibRefCitation>
proposed a broad definition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead." authorityYear="1904" box="[788,903,1843,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[788,903,1843,1866]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Aximopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which embraces the 
<emphasis box="[1139,1247,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">nodularis</emphasis>
species group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Illiger" authorityYear="1807" baseAuthorityName="Lotfalizadeh et al." baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[151,261,1879,1902]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Eurytoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,261,1879,1902]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Eurytoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and includes species that are parasitoids of a variety of endophytic hosts in stems and leaf-mines, beetle galleries in wood and in twigs containing nests of aculeate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[870,1026,1915,1939]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
. The genus is speciose in tropical countries. It is included by 
<bibRefCitation author="Zerova" box="[469,632,1951,1975]" firstAuthor="Zerova" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="1 - 204" refId="ref50239" refString="Zerova, M. D. (2010) Palaearctic species of the genus Eurytoma (Hymenoptera, Chalcidoidea, Eurytomidae): morphological and biological peculiarities, trophical associations and key to determination. Festnik zoologii, 24, 1 - 204." type="journal article" year="2010">Zerova (2010)</bibRefCitation>
in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1878" box="[716,800,1950,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Eurytoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis box="[716,800,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">robusta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Illiger" authorityYear="1807" baseAuthorityName="Lotfalizadeh et al." baseAuthorityYear="2007" box="[1009,1119,1951,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Eurytoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1119,1951,1974]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Eurytoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the presence of a ventral shelf on the mesepisternum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1437,151,536]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
Two species were found associated with asphodels in Europe, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zerova" baseAuthorityYear="1984" box="[906,1016,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collina">
<emphasis box="[906,1016,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">A. collina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the newly described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Delvare &amp; Escolà &amp; Stojanova &amp; Benoit &amp; Lecomte &amp; Askew" authorityYear="2019" box="[1307,1429,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balajasi">
<emphasis box="[1307,1429,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">A. balajasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. They are morphologically extremely close and would not have been separated without molecular data. They are distinguished from other Palaearctic species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead." authorityYear="1904" box="[697,812,224,247]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[697,812,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Aximopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by their biology; they have been reared from galls of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Geoffroy" authorityYear="1762" box="[151,268,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Diplolepis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,268,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Diplolepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Lotfalizadeh" box="[374,653,260,285]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Lotfalizadeh" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="73 - 85" refId="ref49325" refString="Lotfalizadeh, H., Rasplus, J. - Y. &amp; Delvare, G. (2006) Rose gall wasps and their associated fauna (Hymenoptera) in Iran. Redia, 89, 73 - 85." type="journal article" year="2006">
Lotfalizadeh 
<emphasis box="[527,585,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Askew" box="[667,880,260,285]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Askew" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 60" refId="ref47526" refString="Askew, R. R., Plantard, O., Gomez, J. F., Nieves, M. H. &amp; Nieves-Aldrey, J. L. (2006) Catalogue of parasitoids and inquilines in galls of Aylacini, Diplolepidini and Pediaspidini (Hym., Cynipidae) in the West Palaearctic. Zootaxa, 1301, 1 - 60." type="journal article" year="2006">
Askew 
<emphasis box="[754,813,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
) and, as here reported, from seeds of asphodels. Other European 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ashmead." authorityYear="1904" box="[339,454,296,319]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[339,454,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Aximopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with known biology are parasitoids of xylophagous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[1144,1267,295,320]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Zerova" box="[1284,1432,295,320]" firstAuthor="Zerova" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref50209" refString="Zerova, M. D. (1995) Parasitic Hymenoptera - Eurytominae and Eudecatominae of Palaearctics. National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine, Kiev, 460 pp." type="book" year="1995">Zerova 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zerova" box="[151,209,332,356]" firstAuthor="Zerova" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 204" refId="ref50239" refString="Zerova, M. D. (2010) Palaearctic species of the genus Eurytoma (Hymenoptera, Chalcidoidea, Eurytomidae): morphological and biological peculiarities, trophical associations and key to determination. Festnik zoologii, 24, 1 - 204." type="journal article" year="2010">2010</bibRefCitation>
) or of aculeate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[386,538,333,357]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
nesting in twigs (
<bibRefCitation author="Zerova" box="[741,889,332,357]" firstAuthor="Zerova" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="ref50209" refString="Zerova, M. D. (1995) Parasitic Hymenoptera - Eurytominae and Eudecatominae of Palaearctics. National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine, Kiev, 460 pp." type="book" year="1995">Zerova 1995</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zerova" box="[901,959,332,356]" firstAuthor="Zerova" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 204" refId="ref50239" refString="Zerova, M. D. (2010) Palaearctic species of the genus Eurytoma (Hymenoptera, Chalcidoidea, Eurytomidae): morphological and biological peculiarities, trophical associations and key to determination. Festnik zoologii, 24, 1 - 204." type="journal article" year="2010">2010</bibRefCitation>
) and are often collected on dead trunks or branches. Morphologically 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zerova" baseAuthorityYear="1984" box="[468,582,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collina">
<emphasis box="[468,582,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">A. collina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Delvare &amp; Escolà &amp; Stojanova &amp; Benoit &amp; Lecomte &amp; Askew" authorityYear="2019" box="[645,770,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Eurytomidae" genus="Aximopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="balajasi">
<emphasis box="[645,770,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">A. balajasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from their congeners by the following characters: lower face with radiating raised carinulae reaching above lower margin of antennal toruli (
<figureCitation box="[1317,1423,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 27" captionStartId="62.[151,264,1488,1510]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,183,1474]" captionTargetId="figure@62.[151,1436,183,1475]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 27A–F. Aximopsis balajasi. A–E, ♀. F, ♂. A, head in frontal view. B, same in dorsal view. C, antenna. D, propodeum. E, procoxa in anterior view. F, antenna. A, D &amp; E, ex A. ramosus, Vizzini, Monte Iblei, Sicilia, Italy. B &amp; C, holotype ♀, ex A. ramosus, Aléria, Vaccaja, Corse, France [voucher GDEL1610]. F, ex A. ramosus, Sòller, Mallorca, Spain." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668006/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 27A</figureCitation>
), pedicel without basidorsal constriction (
<figureCitation box="[603,707,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURES 27" captionStartId="62.[151,264,1488,1510]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,183,1474]" captionTargetId="figure@62.[151,1436,183,1475]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIGURES 27A–F. Aximopsis balajasi. A–E, ♀. F, ♂. A, head in frontal view. B, same in dorsal view. C, antenna. D, propodeum. E, procoxa in anterior view. F, antenna. A, D &amp; E, ex A. ramosus, Vizzini, Monte Iblei, Sicilia, Italy. B &amp; C, holotype ♀, ex A. ramosus, Aléria, Vaccaja, Corse, France [voucher GDEL1610]. F, ex A. ramosus, Sòller, Mallorca, Spain." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668006/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 27C</figureCitation>
), clava effectively 1-segmented with all its segments fused (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 28" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[195,1436,221,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 28A–E. Aximopsis collina (Zerova), ♀. A, habitus. B, head in posterior view [SEM photograph], C, clava [SEM photograph]. D, petiole in lateral view [SEM photograph], E, same in ventral view. A &amp; E, ex A. ramosus, Banyuls-sur-Mer, Pyrénées-Orientales, France. B–D, female collected by sweeping at Cébazan, Hérault, France." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668008/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 28C</figureCitation>
), ventral shelf of mesepisternum short and distinctly elbowed with epicnemium (
<figureCitation box="[1137,1226,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="61.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[244,1363,707,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[155,1431,661,1890]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 26. Aximopsis balajasi Delvare sp. n., ♀ ex A. ramosus from Sòller, Mallorca, Spain." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668004/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs 26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1241,1294,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURES 28" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[195,1436,221,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 28A–E. Aximopsis collina (Zerova), ♀. A, habitus. B, head in posterior view [SEM photograph], C, clava [SEM photograph]. D, petiole in lateral view [SEM photograph], E, same in ventral view. A &amp; E, ex A. ramosus, Banyuls-sur-Mer, Pyrénées-Orientales, France. B–D, female collected by sweeping at Cébazan, Hérault, France." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668008/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">28A</figureCitation>
); setation of fore wing entirely white and marginal vein shorter than both the stigmal and postmarginal veins (
<figureCitation box="[1238,1325,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="61.[151,250,1911,1933]" captionTargetBox="[244,1363,707,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[155,1431,661,1890]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 26. Aximopsis balajasi Delvare sp. n., ♀ ex A. ramosus from Sòller, Mallorca, Spain." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668004/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Figs 26</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1337,1390,512,536]" captionStart="FIGURES 28" captionStartId="63.[151,264,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[195,1436,221,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@63.[151,1436,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 28A–E. Aximopsis collina (Zerova), ♀. A, habitus. B, head in posterior view [SEM photograph], C, clava [SEM photograph]. D, petiole in lateral view [SEM photograph], E, same in ventral view. A &amp; E, ex A. ramosus, Banyuls-sur-Mer, Pyrénées-Orientales, France. B–D, female collected by sweeping at Cébazan, Hérault, France." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2668008/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">28A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
